<HL> Sears and Disney Agree
On a Mickey Mouse Deal</HL>
<DD> 11/19/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> S DIS
RETAILING (RET) </IN>
<DATELINE> CHICAGO  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. and Walt Disney Co. announced a Mickey Mouse business deal. 

   Officials of the two companies, accompanied by Mickey, Minnie Mouse and Winnie-the-Pooh, signed a 10-year agreement giving Sears exclusive rights to develop clothing, toys and other products using certain Disney characters. 

   The characters include those in new Disney animated films as well as those in Disney's library of full-length animated films. 
Chicago-based Sears won't have exclusive rights to what Burbank, Calif.-based Disney calls its "standard characters" -- Mickey and Minnie, Donald Duck and Goofy, among others -- although it will be able to develop products using the characters. 
Sears also will develop a Disney brand of merchandise. 

   Sears's line of Winnie-the-Pooh clothes and accessories, developed under a previous 22-year-old exclusive licensing agreement with Disney, has generated sales of more than $1 billion in the past decade, the company said. 

   Sears agreed to promote at least two animated Disney films annually in its stores and catalogs and to sponsor two attractions at Walt Disney World in Orlando, Fla. 
Sears officials declined, however, to say how much the retailer would spend on the ventures. 

</TEXT>
