   LOS ANGELES -- The company that controls the rights to the
"Winnie the Pooh" stories and characters filed suit against
Walt Disney Co. in Los Angeles Superior Court, charging
breach of contract in connection with videocassette and
certain other revenues it says it is owed.
   Stephen Slesinger Inc. filed the lawsuit, which bears some
similarity to a suit filed by singer Peggy Lee, who supplied
voices and co-authored songs for the film "Lady and the
Tramp." Her contract was drawn up in 1952, well before the
age of video, and she and Disney have different
interpretations of language in the document as to whether she
is owed a share of the profits from Disney's successful video
release of the film years later. She is seeking $50 million
in a jury trial set to begin Monday in Los Angeles Superior
Court.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Slesinger lawsuit charges that Disney failed to make
payments for the release of several Winnie the Pooh videos
and for certain other rights, including merchandising. The
contract mentioned in the suit, which seeks unspecified
damages, was signed in 1961 and amended in 1983 after a
series of disputes, according to attorney Barry B. Langberg.
A Disney spokesman said Disney hadn't seen the suit and
couldn't comment.
</TEXT>
