<HEAD>British Petroleum Gives Up Plans For Drill Near Pooh Corner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Petroleum has dropped its bid to drill for
oil next to a southern English forest where A.A. Milne conjured up
the immortal Winnie the Pooh more than 60 years ago, the Osberver
newspaper reported Sunday.
   It said the giant oil firm decided not to appeal the East Sussex
County Council's refusal to grant a test-drilling permit for the
area near Ashdown Forest.
   Milne's son, Christopher Robin Milne, 67, was quoted as saying,
however: ``There never can be a total victory while it is
government policy to drill for oil regardless of what lies on the
surface.
   ``They will drill anywhere, except possibly under Buckingham
Palace.''
   In 1925 the Milne family moved from London to the Sussex County
woodlands, near Upper Hartfield village, which became the home of
Christopher and his Bear of Very Little Brain.
