<HEAD>`China Beach,' `Wonder Years' Among Humanitas Prize Winners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``China Beach'' and ``The Wonder Years''
were among winners Thursday of 1989 Humanitas Prizes, given for
network programs displaying ``values that enrich the viewing
public.''
   The 15th annual cash prizes were also awarded to an edition of
the ``CBS Schoolbreak Special'' and an episode from ABC's ``The New
Adventures of Winnie the Pooh.''
   NBC's documentary ``Destined to Live,'' about breast cancer, also
was singled out to receive a Humanitas prize.
   There were no awards for television movies this year because
Humanitas organizers felt no project deserved recognition.
   Patricia Green, the writer of ``China Beach's'' ``Promised Land''
episode, was given a $15,000 prize for her dramatization of the
absurdity of racial prejudice and her portrayal of the importance of
peace.
   In the 30-minute category, Matthew Carlson took a $10,000
Humanitas prize for writing the ``Pottery Will Get You Somewhere''
episode of ``The Wonder Years.'' Carlson's segment dealt with a
family's struggle with new roles, and a child's response to his
parents' failure to communicate.
   A $10,000 award was presented to writer Alan Gansberg in the
children's live action competition. Gansberg's script for ``My Past
is My Own'' on the ``CBS Schoolbreak Special'' explored the power of
seemingly powerless people and the theme that today's freedoms are
the result of earlier sacrifices.
   For children's animation, Doug Hutchinson and Larry Bernard will
split $10,000 for scripting the ``Find Her, Keep Her'' episode of
``The New Adventures of Winnie the Pooh.'' The episode examined the
need to both hold onto and let go of love.
   The prizes were sponsored by the Human Family Institute, a
non-profit organizition dedicated to the humanities.
   The Rev. Elwood Kieser, president of the institute, said future
awards ceremonies would recognize programs presented by public and
cable television and feature films.
</TEXT>
