<TEXT>     Once a week, for about a half-hour, Amrit and three other preschoolers
gather in a small room in the Adventure Children's Center in Union City. There
they follow the instructions of Lin Stefanick, who leads them through games
that teach them how to operate the computer.;    "Basically, it's something
everyone is going to use, so why not get them comfortable with it," said Carol
Lechleitner, who owns the Computertots franchise for Alameda and Santa Clara
counties. "It's really giving them a comfort level so they feel good about
trying something new.";    The Computertots program, which was started by two
Virginia special education teachers in 1984, tries to make computer learning
fun. Each class begins with a song about computers, using the music from
familiar nursery rhymes. The program has a stuffed turtle for a mascot, called
Computer Turtle, who the kids hug before class to get them going.;    Then the
children use educational software to learn about numbers and letters. In one
popular lesson a cookie will pop up on one side of the screen and kids will
have to match it to a set of three cookies on the other side of the screen,
Lechleitner said. That teaches them recognition, and reinforces counting
skills, she said.;    "The kids don't realize this is supposed to be
learning," said Cindy Breeden, whose 4-year-old daughter, Jennifer, takes
Computertots at the St. James Christian Preschool in San Leandro.;   
Lechleitner has set up Computertots classes in 21 preschools in Alameda
County, and plans to set up classes in Santa Clara County in the fall, she
said. The series of four half-hour classes costs about $30. When the children
are finished, they will know about the parts of the computer, how to turn it
on and off, and how to do rudimentary programs.;    "It's really something the
children look forward to," said Eleanor Gothberg, who runs the Adventure
Children's Center. "I think it will make them self-confident when they
encounter computers in elementary school. All the elementary schools have them
now."; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The Newark Recreation Division will sponsor a
Computertots series on Thursdays, starting March 7. The series, open to
children 3 to 5 years old, will cost $36. If interested, call (415) 522-9020.  </TEXT>
