<HEAD>Experienced Storyteller, Barbara Bush, to Read on Radio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush, who has been reading stories to
her own children and grandchildren for years, reaches out to a
wider audience this weekend with a nationally broadcast radio
series.
   Borrowing a page from former New York Mayor Fiorello La Guardia,
the first lady will be reading children's stories over the ABC
radio network in a weekly series called ``Mrs. Bush's Story Time.''
   She'll also be offering tips in her 10 half-hour broadcasts to
parents on reading aloud to children. It's all part of her family
literacy campaign.
   Unlike New York's Depression-era mayor, who broadcast the comics
during a newspaper strike, Mrs. Bush is eschewing the funny pages
and sticking with children's literature.
   But she will get an assist from the cartoon world.
   Mrs. Bush will be reading her stories to such familiar
characters as Winnie the Pooh, Garfield, Bugs Bunny, Roger Rabbit,
Mickey and Minnie Mouse and Big Bird, done by their usual cartoon
voices.
   ``I'm not a comic reader,'' snipped Mrs. Bush.
   ``What we're trying to do is encourage families to read to their
children and take them to libraries,'' she explained in an
interview.
   ``We're going to tell them how to stop and talk and how to
explain words'' the kids don't understand, she said.
   ``Mrs. Bush's Story Time'' is a joint project of ABC's Project
Literacy U.S. and the Philadelphia-based Children's Literacy
Initiative.
   Jim Farley, executive producer of the series, calls it ``a
radical departure'' for commercial radio.
   ``American commercial radio stations don't program to kids,'' he
said. ``They don't let kids fill out (ratings) diaries, so they
don't count in the ratings.''
   For children listening to the first lady's broadcasts, ``radio
won't be a jukebox, it will be a source of both entertainment and
stimulation,'' the producer said.
   Mrs. Bush taped the broadcasts in two sittings at ABC's
Washington studios earlier this summer. The cartoon voices were
dubbed in later.
   ``This is an experienced storyteller,'' said Farley. ``She was
terrific.''
   The line up of stories include ``Ira Sleeps Over,'' ``Sylvester
and the Magic Pebble,'' ``The Story of Ferdinand,'' ``The Three
Billy Goats Gruff'' and ``Frog and Toad Together.'' Farley said the
stories are intended to hold the interest of children from ages 3
to 10.
   Mrs. Bush interrupts her own storytelling to ask her listeners
open-ended questions, and each week she offers a reading tip for
parents. Each broadcast ends with such celebrities as Oprah Winfrey
and Bette Midler talking about how reading affected their lives.
   More than 100 radio stations have signed up to air the weekly
broadcasts at various times starting this Saturday and Sunday.
</TEXT>
