<HEAD>Time-Life Books Buys British Children's Book Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A European subsidiary of Time Inc. Monday
announced the purchase of Books for Children, a large British book
club, from Independent Television Publications.
   The price paid for the acquisition by Time-Life Books (Europe)
Inc. was not disclosed.
   In an announcement released in London and made available in New
York, Books for Children was described as Britain's largest quality
hardback book club for children from pre-school age to early teens.
   Its monthly catalogue includes books about such famous characters
as ``Winnie the Pooh'' and ``Thomas the Tank Engine.'' The club is
known for its policy of introducing new, imaginative authors and
illustrators and it sponsors the annual Mother Goose Award for the
most exciting newcomer to British children's book illustration.
   Joe Ward, president and chief executive officer of Time-Life
Books (Europe), said the acquisition is part of the company's
strategy of international expansion and the development of a
significant children's publishing capacity.
   ``We have been interested in obtaining Books for Children for
some time because it is a natural fit for our own plans to grow in
the children's market,'' said Ward.
   Independent Television Publications, owned by 15 independent
television companies in Britain, acts as the magazine publishing arm
of independent television. Its main publication is TV Times,
Britain's second largest selling magazine.
</TEXT>
