<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   A Mother's Lifetime of Secrets Revealed
   ----
   By Julia Just
</HL>
<DATE>
06/17/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<LP>
   In a recent essay, Amy Tan described the acute anxiety she
experienced while working on "The Kitchen God's Wife," her
second novel. A phantom audience of fans and critics looking
over her shoulder, she said, caused a pain in her neck that
later spread to her jaw, resulting in "two cracked teeth and,
finally, a huge dental bill." It didn't help, when, at Ms.
Tan's first literary luncheon, a woman said to her
innocently, "How does it feel to have written your best book
first?"
   That book was the hugely successful "The Joy Luck Club,"
and it was indeed a tough act to follow. If, in the
inflationary world of book publishing, Ms. Tan's debut at
times seemed overpraised -- adjectives like "mesmerizing,"
"brilliant" and "powerful" were plastered all over the
original paperback edition -- the intelligence and clarity of
her voice were astonishing. The novel, composed of delicately
realized vignettes about four first-generation
Chinese-American mothers and their daughters, was clearly the
work of a mature talent.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The Kitchen God's Wife" (Putnam's, 415 pages, $22.95)
also begins with a Chinese-American mother, Winnie, and her
thoroughly American, 40-something daughter, Pearl. Again,
readers can dreamily re-enter a world where every
conversation has a coded meaning, where household objects are
animated by their own rebellious spirits, and where nothing
is an accident ("she's like a Chinese version of Freud," says
Pearl of Winnie). And the new book shares certain leitmotifs
with its predecessor: Loyalty, destiny and luck -- good and
bad -- are once again legacies to be passed on to a younger
generation that often doesn't understand, or want, its
inheritance.
   But where "The Joy Luck Club" was a group portrait, "The
Kitchen God's Wife" above all tells the story of how Winnie
was once Weiwei, the most richly imagined character Ms. Tan
has yet created. The story -- which describes a brutal first
marriage set against turbulent times -- is closely based on
her mother's life in China before, during and after World War
II, and the wartime scenes, especially, have the force of a
compelling oral history. But this is fundamentally a novel:
Its power lies in the author's impressive ability to create a
world.
   One of the sharpest tools at this writer's command is her
ear for dialogue. In almost adversarial, semi-concealing
fashion, conversations arrive at their destinations by
circular paths, everyone present taking something different
from what was said.
   "Whenever my mother talks to me, she begins the
conversation as if we were already in the middle of an
argument," the novel opens. "`Pearl-ah, have to go, no
choice,' my mother said when she phoned last week" -- and so
Pearl is invited to attend, with her husband and two
daughters, her cousin Bao-Bao's engagement party in San
Francisco. In short order, we are introduced to Auntie Helen,
whose first husband, back in China, was Winnie's brother; he
died long before Pearl was born. Only, none of this turns out
to be true. Winnie and Auntie Helen (really Hulan) aren't
even related, but are instead "joined by debts" half a
century old, sworn promises that stretch back to Shanghai in
the '30s, during the time Japan invaded China.
   "I have kept her secrets. She has kept mine," Winnie tells
Pearl. "So you can imagine my anger when Helen told me in her
kitchen . . . that she has decided to let all my secrets
out." Winnie decides she must beat Helen to it, and the
substance of this book is her long, extraordinarily
compelling confession to Pearl the unseen, all-important
listener.
   Winnie lays her life out in gorgeous, raw detail, a
succession of characters -- many of whom, like Helen, grow in
depth and complexity as the book progresses -- and images: a
bolt of peach fabric for a dress that was never made, bombs
"the shape of fish . . . dropping, wobbling" overhead in
wartime, an idyllic mountaintop village called Heaven's
Breath.
   The secret that lies at the heart of Winnie's past is that
she has been married before and that her first husband, a
larger-than-life villain named Wen Fu, is almost certainly
Pearl's father -- not the Chinese-American serviceman who
Winnie joined in California after escaping from China in
1949. While living through war with the Japanese, nightly
rape by her husband, the pillage of her father's property by
Wen Fu's relatives, the rise of the Communist Party in China,
Winnie's talismans are luck, hope and "no regrets." The
"Kitchen God's Wife" of the title, also betrayed in legend by
a villainous husband, is frequently invoked: "Nobody
worshipped her either."
   This novel isn't flawless. The epic struggles at the
story's center are more compelling than Pearl's narration,
which frames the whole and gives it a feeling of unbalance.
Still, after all Winnie's scolding and railing, she does
achieve a kind of beatific resignation, with her hopes
lifting "higher and higher." One sign of this is the statue
she gives Pearl, an image of a new lucky goddess, Lady
Sorrowfree: the ex-Mrs. Kitchen God, divorced.
   ---
   Ms. Just is a free-lance writer in New York.
